# Databricks deploys must run outside the sandbox

The Databricks CLI caches its OAuth token under `~/.databricks/` (outside the
workspace). When a command needs to refresh the token, the sandbox blocks the
write to that cache and the command fails with:

```
forced token refresh: cache update: exit status 161
```

This affects `databricks bundle deploy` (the Terraform layer triggers a refresh),
and can affect `databricks apps deploy`, `databricks sync`, and `databricks auth login`.

## Rule

When running any Databricks CLI command that authenticates, deploys, or syncs,
ALWAYS pass `required_permissions: ["all"]` to the Shell tool so it runs outside
the sandbox.

This includes:
- `databricks bundle deploy` / `databricks bundle validate`
- `databricks apps deploy` / `databricks apps start`
- `databricks sync`
- `databricks auth login`
- `bash scripts/deploy.sh` (the project deploy wrapper)

```
# ✅ GOOD — runs outside the sandbox, token refresh works
Shell(command: "cd aaron && npm run deploy", required_permissions: ["all"])

# ❌ BAD — sandbox blocks token cache write → exit status 161
Shell(command: "cd aaron && npm run deploy")
```

Read-only Databricks calls (e.g. `databricks apps logs`, `... get`, `... list`,
`serving-endpoints query`) generally work in the sandbox with
`required_permissions: ["full_network"]`, but if any of them fail with the
`exit status 161` token error, re-run with `required_permissions: ["all"]`.
